After reviewing the provided evidence, I conclude:
\boxed{B}
Reasoning: Multiple lines of evidence support that paucigranulocytic asthmatics still experience meaningful inflammatory responses. First, biomarkers like fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO) and peripheral blood eosinophil counts correlate strongly with type 2 inflammation regardless of sputum granulocyte numbers. Second, systemic inflammatory markers—including CRP, ESR, IL-6, and sIL-2R—are routinely measured in asthma evaluations and reflect active immune activation. Third, the existence of biologic therapies targeting IL-5 or TSLP—which act downstream of eosinophilic signaling—confirms that type 2 inflammation remains therapeutically relevant even in the absence of prominent neutrophils or granulocytes in sputum. Therefore, the term "paucigranulocytic" does not imply non-inflammatory pathology; instead, it reflects a shift toward different dominant inflammatory drivers. Thus, the original assertion that these patients are truly non-inflammatory must be rejected.\boxed{B}
